 "segments": [
  {
   "start": 0.0,
   "end": 4.66,
   "text": "In China, the man at the shop, the bus driver, your neighbor, they're all de- your uncle"
  },
  {
   "start": 4.66,
   "end": 5.64,
   "text": "or auntie."
  },
  {
   "start": 5.94,
   "end": 8.86,
   "text": "But here's the irony, there's no single Chinese word for uncle at all."
  },
  {
   "start": 9.26,
   "end": 10.12,
   "text": "There are at least 8."
  },
  {
   "start": 10.38,
   "end": 10.98,
   "text": "Let me explain."
  },
  {
   "start": 11.76,
   "end": 15.38,
   "text": "English has one lazy word, uncle, for a whole crowd of different people."
  },
  {
   "start": 16.12,
   "end": 19.48,
   "text": "Chinese refuses to be that vague, it needs to know exactly who you mean."
  },
  {
   "start": 20.0,
   "end": 21.92,
   "text": "Is he your father's brother or your mother's?"
  },
  {
   "start": 22.16,
   "end": 23.96,
   "text": "Is he older than your parent or younger?"
  },
  {
   "start": 24.56,
   "end": 26.04,
   "text": "Is he blood or married in?"
  },
  {
   "start": 26.76,
   "end": 28.22,
   "text": "Every combination is a different word."
  },
  {
   "start": 28.86,
   "end": 32.34,
   "text": "Father's older brother, father's younger brother, mother's brother, the husband of"
  },
  {
   "start": 32.34,
   "end": 35.84,
   "text": "your father's sister, maaang all completely separate terms."
  },
  {
   "start": 36.32,
   "end": 38.34,
   "text": "There's no neutral uncle to fall back on."
  },
  {
   "start": 38.72,
   "end": 40.9,
   "text": "The word itself tells you the exact relationship."
  },
  {
   "start": 41.24,
   "end": 45.14,
   "text": "It's because family structure mattered so much that the language baked it right in."
  },
  {
   "start": 45.6,
   "end": 46.1,
   "text": "Which side?"
  },
  {
   "start": 46.38,
   "end": 46.94,
   "text": "Which generation?"
  },
  {
   "start": 47.38,
   "end": 48.1,
   "text": "Which order of birth?"
  },
  {
   "start": 48.58,
   "end": 49.54,
   "text": "You don't just say uncle."
  },
  {
   "start": 50.02,
   "end": 54.74,
   "text": "You say precisely where he sits in the family and yet, Chinese uses these very same family"
  },
  {
   "start": 54.74,
   "end": 55.76,
   "text": "words for total strangers."
  },
  {
   "start": 56.3,
   "end": 61.7,
   "text": "You call an older man, uncle, an older woman, auntie, a young woman, big sister, as a sign"
  },
  {
   "start": 61.7,
   "end": 62.62,
   "text": "of warmth and respect."
  },
  {
   "start": 63.38,
   "end": 67.08,
   "text": "Everyone gets slotted into the family, so Chinese can't translate uncle with a single"
  },
  {
   "start": 67.08,
   "end": 67.4,
   "text": "word."
  },
  {
   "start": 67.66,
   "end": 70.96,
   "text": "It has a whole map of them, but it'll happily call a stranger on the street your uncle."
  },
  {
   "start": 71.56,
   "end": 75.5,
   "text": "A language incredibly precise about family that treats the entire world like one."
  },
  {
   "start": 76.02,
   "end": 77.4,
   "text": "Want to actually start learning Chinese?"
  },
  {
   "start": 77.9,
   "end": 81.74,
   "text": "Discover thousands of free exercises and more learning content on stacktags.io."
  }
 ]
